<a href="javascript:card_browser(557)">Maelstrom</a> x1<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(425}<a href="javascript:card_browser({411)">Orwin</a>&#39;s Gaze</a> x1<br>
Bloom x1<br>
<br>
TOTAL: 40 cards<br>
<br>
&quot;Pure Energy&quot;<br>
By: Jamie Kelly (XwarlocK)   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> <embed src="http://www.decktech.net/magination/pure_energy2.wav" autostart="true""><br>
<br>
Strategy:<br>
<br>
In a nutshell, use Obgren to Cleanse Quido Swarm to KT/Bograth and use Shaper&#39;s Apprentice to cast Kybar&#39;s Echo, put down a Climbing Staff, and play a recurring Quido Swarm to gain energy.  I first thought this up after I read what Climbing Staff really does and how Kybar&#39;s Echo really didn&#39;t fix the Ullig loop after all.  Here are the details:<br>
<br>
Aula is used for typical pure card drawing and combo digging.  Try to go first with her.  There are only 4 cards to the combo (Cleansing, Climbing Staff, Kybar&#39;s Echo and Quido Swarm) and various tricks to get them later if needed.  Start with Cloud Sceptre and J&#39;lith and 3 random.  J&#39;lith can be a corrupt breaker else play any Arderial/Universal Relics and any Bubble Xyx&#39;s and then use Aula&#39;s Windsight.  Use the Bubble Xyx&#39;s Burst and/or Sorreah&#39;s Dream it to draw more cards.  Once you have exhausted your card drawing, begin to use the Cloud Sceptre to cycle your hand.  The most important card to dig for is the Cleansing.  Use Sorreah&#39;s Dreams to Mindwinds additional times if necessary.  Let&#39;s assume you have the combo in your hand now.<br>
<br>
Obgren sets up the combo by immediately playing a Cleansing.  Here you must use Obgren to hack &quot;Core&quot; to say &quot;Paradwyn&quot; and then choose Quido Swarm and Cleanse it to be Kybar&#39;s Teeth/Bograth.  If this is all Obgren can do, you are fine.  Anything else is a perk.  More card drawing and additional Cleansings are good options here.  (More on this later)  If you don&#39;t have a Quido Swarm in hand but one is in your discard, you can still use the Bog Stone to go get it.  In fact, if you want to play aggressive, you can ditch all Quido Swarms safely to Aula&#39;s Cloud Sceptre on first turn.  You opponents will either laugh or cry at the random assortment of cards that end up in your discard pile.  <br>
<br>
Shaper&#39;s Apprentice executes the combo by playing a Kybar&#39;s Echo and playing (yes, playing) a Climbing Staff.  Now you are in a game state where playing a KT creature adds one energy to your Magi (effect Higher Ground) and if a KT creature is discarded from play it is returned to your hand instead.  Now, Quido Swarm is KT/Bograth.  Play a Quido Swarm for 0 (no other Bograth creature in play for you) and gain 1 energy.  Quido Swarm is discarded from 0 energy immediate game rule.  It is instead returned to your hand.  You are still in your play creatures step and net 1 energy on your Magi.  Repeat until you have enough energy to be comfortable.  I usually go with 200.  You are still in your play creatures step.  Play Sea Barl, Greater Gargagnor, and any left over Bubble Xyx&#39;s.  Draw cards like mad.  Dream Twist out the Sea Barl for a Bubble Xyx in your discard.  Burst.  Sorreah&#39;s Dream Burst.  Hopefully you can cycle the rest of your deck by now.<br>
<br>
Next comes the endgame phase.  Destroy all your opponent&#39;s creatures with Stone Storm, Thunderquake and/or Ormagon.  Don&#39;t forget to Unearth that Stone Storm using the Greater Gargagnor to play it twice a turn (more with Sorreah&#39;s Dreams).  Now, try to Maelstrom for the kill (since Shaper&#39;s Apprentice is Orothe too).  Do all you can to defeat your opponent&#39;s Magi each turn.  The most important thing to do now is to protect the energy on your Magi using Climbing Staffs and other tricks outlined below.<br>
<br>
That&#39;s all there is to it.  It seems simple but there are hundreds of more options with this deck versus other deck types.  If for some reason you get low on energy you can repeat the Kybar&#39;s Echo/Quido Swarm to gain more.  After some practice you can make your turns very quick so reaching time limit is less of a worry.  I recorded some test draws and got the combo first turn with Aula&#39;s starting energy (14), 19 out of 20 times.  The keys to this part were Bubble Xyx, Sorreah&#39;s Dream, and Aula.  Also, quick self defeat is paramount.  Don&#39;t let your opponent get any more turns for card drawing than you have to.  There is a multitude of ways to defeat yourself including: Thunderquake, Stone Storm, Resonate, Sandswirl, etc.  Don&#39;t get too greedy with card drawing if you have the combo and some good meta-game support in your hand.  Remember you will be able to draw many more cards with Shaper&#39;s Apprentice once the combo is executed.<br>
<br>
Defense:<br>
<br>
As with any combo deck, there are some weaknesses.  Public enemy number one is CONTROL and your opponents&#39; knowledge of the combo.  A good control player can deny you the plays necessary to make the combo work.  Phrups, Deep Wellisks, Bloom, Bahzrah&#39;s Pendant, Rayje&#39;s Belt, etc. are all hindrances.  When you come up with Obgren or Shaper&#39;s Apprentice, you must try to draw out the Phrups etc. using Rayje&#39;s Belt, Thunderquake, Stone Storm, Sandswirl, Beam of Light, Resonate, or Ormagon.  That&#39;s 7 opportunities which you should try to hold in your hand if you face a control deck.<br>
<br>
The second problem deck type is removal/big zot.  Removal through Tidal Wave/Thunderquake/Cataclysm, etc. followed up by Hubdra&#39;s Spear/Abraxin&#39;s Crown-Storm Cloud/Ninx-Stare Down with a Rayje&#39;s sword in play is a game winner here.  With no Rayje&#39;s Sword in play, pitching a Climbing Staff can (usually) do the job.  In other cases, you must use that Bloom.  Bloom/(relic removal) the Hubdra&#39;s Spear/Abraxin&#39;s Crown/Rayje&#39;s Sword etc. and hope they don&#39;t have another.  See below for a better method using Cleansing in the Tricks section.<br>
<br>
Any other creature beatdown based deck can be handled with the massive re-usable creature removal followed up by a &quot;zot to the dome&quot; with Maelstrom (in the immortal words of Gregory Kelton).  Don&#39;t worry about having no creatures in play.  Who cares if they attack you for 35e horde?  It&#39;s a drop in the bucket when you have 200e.  You can deal with those creatures next turn.<br>
<br>
A surprise I got from Paul Heaver (great guy and awesome player) was Bloom/Impact on a big creature in response to Shaper&#39;s Apprentice combo start-up.  The next time around I made sure to Maelstrom first hoping for no Climbing Staff.  Another good defense add is Tranquility to get around it too.<br>
<br>
Tricks:<br>
<br>
Cleansing is not only for the Quido Swarm.  Its a great offense and defense too.  The Abwyn&#39;s Quill is in the deck for the possible first turn Cleansing but if you have an extra cleansing on Obgren, go ahead and use it to Cleanse Abwyn&#39;s Quill to be KT.  Now, when Shaper&#39;s Apprentice comes up you can use the Quill again for your cycled Cleansings, hacking your Ormagon, etc.  Cleanse your Maelstrom to KT so you can Unearth it and play it twice each turn (or more with Sorreah&#39;s Dreams).  Cleanse your Cloud Sceptre to KT for more card cycling.  Cleanse your Bog Stone and hack it when you use it to get any creature from your discard pile.  The Cleansing can also be a great defense card too.  Cleanse an opponents relics to Underneath or KT so they can&#39;t play them.  Some good choices would be Hubdra&#39;s Spear, Abraxin&#39;s Crown, Rayje&#39;s Sword, Warrior Boots, Rayje&#39;s Belt, etc.<br>
<br>
Other cards in the deck serve some specific purposes.  If you have to cycle some important cards on Aula&#39;s first Windsight, you can get one back using Orwin&#39;s Gaze.  This may be necessary after you see what your opponent is playing.  If you fear the Storm of Fishes, get back that Abraxin&#39;s Crown.  Low on Climbing Staffs, get one back.  <br>
<br>
The Mantle of Shadows is for the random Entomb but a double Entomb is next to impossible to deal with in this version.  Earlier versions contained some Urhails but we took them out for the environment we expected.  An Entomb added to the deck might make for a good defense option as well (under the Mantle).  Sandswirl and Abwyn&#39;s Quill are good defense against an opposing O&#39;qua.  J&#39;lith is mostly in the deck to fill up a draw slot to decrease the chance of drawing combo pieces in your opening hand but it is also useful for Dream Twist fodder.  <br>
<br>
Credits:<br>
<br>
Foremost, my congratulations to Stephen Strand for taking this deck to the final match of the GenCon MND 2002 World Championships.  And, I want to grant my greatest respect to Matt Loomis for his superior performance in establishing the control lock and becoming the 2002 MND World Champion.  I watched Matt play the finals and he is definitely a superb player and worthy of the title.<br>
<br>
I also want to credit Stephen Strand, Van Russell, Jerry Hill, Dr. Bob, Gregory Kelton, Roy Jones, and Ron Padgett for their help with the deck.  Stephen, Van, and Jerry all had some great additions to the deck and everyone had some great feedback.  Special thanks to Van for all the Cleansing tech ideas and to Dr. Bob for the deck name.<br>
<br>
Epilogue:<br>
<br>
I&#39;ve heard everyone&#39;s opinions on the morals of playing broken combo decks.  I avoid playing combo decks at our local tournament scene for fear of driving away newer players.  But when I go to a big tournament, I&#39;m there to win while at the same time being a good sport.  Yes, this a broken deck.  Yes, some things need to be fixed.  Yes, it can be beaten, but only by the right player with the right deck types.  I&#39;m sure there will soon be some clarifications and possible MRPs so until then, I discourage anyone from playing a deck like this at your local tournament scene.  Let&#39;s just all have some fun playing Magi-Nation with our friends and be good sports about it.     <br>
<br>
Jamie Kelly (XwarlocK)<br>
